As we cannot, I think, ascribe his silence to accident, still less to the author's indifference to what was passing around him, the reason must be sought in some other cause. Possi- bly, it was found in England at that time, as it has recently been found in Spain, that great and stirring public events still leave a large portion of the people, in the remote pro- vinces, to follow their ordinary calling-s, and do not, for a time, at least, seriously affect the domestic industry of the country. But if this be not thought a sufficient excuse for the author’s careful exclusion of all extrinsic subJects from the manuscript, we may safely ascribe it to the characteristic cantion of Sir Peter Legh.
